Cardiovascular Risk: Lifestyle, Blood
Pressure & Global Hypertension Context
Final Exam Data Science Project - Technical Report
Problem formulation
This project investigates whether lifestyle and basic clinical indicators can explain and predict
cardiovascular disease risk. The real-world problem is translated into a binary classification task:
predicting whether cardiovascular disease is present.
Data sources
Source 1 is the Kaggle Cardiovascular Disease Dataset with patient-level clinical and lifestyle variables.
Source 2 is the WHO / Our World in Data hypertension prevalence dataset, which provides country-level
public-health context.
Hypotheses
H1: BMI and blood pressure increase risk. H2: Physical activity reduces risk. H3: Multivariable models
outperform a single-factor baseline. H4: Patient-level blood-pressure signals align with global
hypertension patterns.
Mathematical background
The project uses Pearson correlation, logistic regression, random forest classification, confusion
matrices, ROC curves and ROC-AUC. Logistic regression estimates P(Y=1|X) using the sigmoid
function.
Methods
The workflow includes data validation, clinical outlier filtering, feature engineering, exploratory analysis,
model training, cross-validation, model comparison and interpretation.
Evaluation
Models are evaluated with accuracy, precision, recall, F1-score and ROC-AUC. A single-factor
hypertension model is used as a baseline to test whether a multivariable model adds value.
Limitations
The data is observational, so the analysis does not prove causality. Patient-level and country-level data
have different granularities and are used together for contextual interpretation, not direct row-level
merging.
Conclusion
The project is designed to satisfy the exam requirements while also functioning as a portfolio-ready data
science project. Its strength is the complete workflow: problem formulation, math, code, analysis,
interpretation and documentation.
